<!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════
     MODULE 1.01 — INTRO TO CLINICAL NEUROLOGY
═══════════════════════════════════════════════ -->

<section class="page-section anchor" id="cortex-layers">
  <div class="section-header">
    <span class="section-tag">1.01</span>
    <h2 class="section-title">Cortical Layers, Neurons & History</h2>
  </div>

  <h3>⭐ Six Layers of the Cerebral Cortex</h3>
  <div class="tbl-wrap">
    <table>
      <tr><th>Layer</th><th>Name</th><th>Key Features</th><th>High Yield</th></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">I</td><td>Molecular Layer</td><td>Outermost; sparse cell bodies</td><td>—</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">II</td><td>External Granule Cell Layer</td><td>Densely packed small neurons</td><td>—</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">III</td><td>External Pyramidal Cell Layer</td><td>More prominent pyramidal cells</td><td>—</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">IV</td><td>Internal Granule Cell Layer</td><td>Receives thalamic input</td><td>Thalamic relay</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl" style="background:#fff3e0"><strong>V ⭐</strong></td><td><strong>Internal Pyramidal Cell Layer</strong></td><td><strong>Largest pyramidal cells; Betz cells</strong></td><td class="hl-red"><strong>Major output layer; corticospinal tract & motor control</strong></td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">VI</td><td>Multiform Layer</td><td>Diverse cell types</td><td>—</td></tr>
    </table>
  </div>

  <div class="callout yellow"><strong>⭐ High-Yield</strong> Betz cells = Layer V = Internal Pyramidal Cell Layer → motor output via corticospinal tract. "Layer 5 drives!"</div>

  <h3>History of Neuroscience — Key People</h3>
  <div class="tbl-wrap">
    <table>
      <tr><th>Person</th><th>Title</th><th>Key Contributions</th></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">Santiago Ramón y Cajal</td><td>Father of Modern <em>Neuroscience</em></td><td>Neuron Doctrine (neurons are separate, individual cells); identified 6 layers of cortex; neuron as functional unit of brain</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">Camillo Golgi</td><td>—</td><td>Golgi stain (silver staining); proposed continuous network theory (debunked by Cajal); shared Nobel 1906</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">Jean-Martin Charcot</td><td>Father of Modern <em>Neurology</em></td><td>Named multiple sclerosis; Charcot's Triad (fever, RUQ pain, jaundice); Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease; first neurological CPC</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Charles Sherrington</td><td>—</td><td>Coined term "synapse"</td></tr>
    </table>
  </div>

  <div class="callout red"><strong>⭐ Trick</strong> Cajal = Neuroscience. Charcot = Neurology. Don't mix them up!</div>
</section>

<!-- NEURON -->

<section class="page-section anchor" id="neuron-parts">
  <h3>Parts of a Neuron</h3>
  <div class="tbl-wrap">
    <table>
      <tr><th>Structure</th><th>Function</th><th>High Yield</th></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">Dendrites</td><td>Receive signals; INPUT zone</td><td>Branches profusely; extends ~100s µm from soma</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">Cell Body (Soma)</td><td>INTEGRATION zone; metabolic center; houses nucleus & DNA</td><td>—</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">Axon Hillock</td><td>Connects soma to axon; action potential initiation</td><td>—</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">Axon</td><td>CONDUCTION zone; transmits electrical impulses away from soma</td><td>Single extension</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">Myelin</td><td>Insulating layer; rapid signal transmission</td><td>CNS → Oligodendrocytes; PNS → Schwann cells</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">Nodes of Ranvier</td><td>Gaps in myelin; saltatory conduction</td><td>Key for rapid nerve impulse conduction</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">Axon Terminals (Synaptic Boutons)</td><td>OUTPUT zone; release neurotransmitters into synaptic cleft</td><td>Presynaptic component</td></tr>
    </table>
  </div>

  <h3>Neuron Classification</h3>
  <div class="two-col">
    <div class="tbl-wrap">
      <table>
        <tr><th colspan="2">By Shape</th></tr>
        <tr><td class="hl">Unipolar</td><td>Single process; exclusively sensory</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="hl">Bipolar ⭐</td><td>1 axon + 1 dendrite; <strong>olfactory epithelium & retina</strong></td></tr>
        <tr><td class="hl">Multipolar</td><td>1 axon + ≥2 dendrites; Golgi neurons, pyramidal, Purkinje, granule cells</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="hl">Pseudounipolar</td><td>Single process → branches; ALL are sensory</td></tr>
      </table>
    </div>
    <div class="tbl-wrap">
      <table>
        <tr><th colspan="2">By Function</th></tr>
        <tr><td class="hl">Motor (Efferent)</td><td>Brain/spinal cord → muscles; e.g., UMN, LMN via corticospinal tract</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="hl">Sensory (Afferent)</td><td>Periphery → CNS (post-central gyrus); touch, sound, light</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="hl">Interneuron (Connector)</td><td>Neither motor nor sensory; reflexes, neural circuitry in CNS</td></tr>
      </table>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h3>Glial Cells</h3>
  <div class="tbl-wrap">
    <table>
      <tr><th>Cell</th><th>Location</th><th>Function</th><th>Tumor</th></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">Oligodendrocytes</td><td>CNS</td><td>Produce myelin in CNS; one cell myelinates multiple axons</td><td>Oligodendroglioma</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">Astrocytes ⭐</td><td>CNS</td><td>Star-shaped; most numerous; nourishment; protective barrier (BBB)</td><td>Glioma/Astrocytoma (most common); Glioblastoma (most aggressive)</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">Ependymal Cells</td><td>CNS</td><td>CSF homeostasis; brain metabolism; <strong>waste clearance</strong></td><td>—</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">Microglia</td><td>CNS</td><td>Resident immune cells; scavengers; respond to pathogens</td><td>—</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">Schwann Cells</td><td>PNS</td><td>Myelinate PNS axons; axon maintenance & regeneration</td><td>Schwannoma</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">Satellite Cells</td><td>PNS</td><td>Maintenance/repair of skeletal muscle</td><td>—</td></tr>
    </table>
  </div>

  <div class="callout blue"><strong>⭐ Memory</strong> Glioblastoma originates from <strong>astrocytes</strong> — most aggressive brain tumor. Astrocytoma/Glioma = astrocytes = most common. Oligodendroglioma = less common.</div>

  <h3>Neuron Doctrine (Cajal) vs Golgi's Theory</h3>
  <div class="compare">
    <div class="compare-col">
      <div class="compare-col-head teal">Cajal — Neuron Doctrine ✓</div>
      <div class="compare-col-body">
        <ul>
          <li>Neurons are <strong>independent, separate cells</strong></li>
          <li>Information transmitted across <strong>synapses</strong> (tiny gaps)</li>
          <li>Neuron = functional unit of the brain</li>
          <li>Used Golgi's stain technique to prove this</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="compare-col">
      <div class="compare-col-head red">Golgi's Theory ✗ (debunked)</div>
      <div class="compare-col-body">
        <ul>
          <li>Neurons were <strong>continuous</strong> with each other</li>
          <li>Nearly endless network of connected tubes</li>
          <li>Synapse concept not recognized</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- CSF & MENINGES -->

<section class="page-section anchor" id="csf-flow">
  <div class="section-header">
    <span class="section-tag">1.01</span>
    <h2 class="section-title">CSF, Meninges & Brain Support</h2>
  </div>

  <h3>Meninges (DAP)</h3>
  <div class="tbl-wrap">
    <table>
      <tr><th>Layer</th><th>Description</th><th>Clinical Relevance</th></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">Dura Mater</td><td>Outermost; 2 sublayers (periosteal + meningeal)</td><td>Epidural hematoma, subdural hematoma</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">Arachnoid Mater</td><td>Middle; NO blood vessels; resembles spider web</td><td>Subarachnoid space = site of SAH; CSF cushion</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">Pia Mater ⭐</td><td>Innermost; <strong>contains nerves and blood vessels</strong></td><td>Directly covers brain; most vascular layer</td></tr>
    </table>
  </div>

  <h3>⭐ CSF Flow — Mnemonic</h3>
  <div class="mnemonic">
    <div class="mnemonic-label">🧠 Mnemonic</div>
    <div class="mnemonic-text">"Come Let's Migrate To States For Money, Love, and Sex"</div>
    <div class="mnemonic-expand">
      <strong>C</strong>horoid plexus → <strong>L</strong>ateral ventricles → foramen of <strong>M</strong>onro → <strong>T</strong>hird ventricle → aqueduct of <strong>S</strong>ylvius → <strong>F</strong>ourth ventricle → foramen of <strong>M</strong>agendie &amp; foramen of <strong>L</strong>uschka → <strong>S</strong>ubarachnoid space
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="callout teal"><strong>Key Facts</strong> ~500 cc CSF produced daily by choroid plexus (ependymal cells). Monro-Kellie Doctrine: cranial cavity = fixed volume of brain tissue + blood + CSF. Hydrocephalus → emergent if untreated → herniation. Causative agent in PH: TB meningitis.</div>

  <h3>Ventricular System</h3>
  <div class="algo">
    <div class="flow">
      <div class="flow-step">
        <div class="flow-num">1</div>
        <div class="flow-content"><h5>Choroid Plexus</h5>Produces CSF; located in ependymal cells</div>
      </div>
      <div class="flow-step">
        <div class="flow-num">2</div>
        <div class="flow-content"><h5>Lateral Ventricles (Right & Left)</h5>Connected to 3rd ventricle via foramen of Monro</div>
      </div>
      <div class="flow-step">
        <div class="flow-num">3</div>
        <div class="flow-content"><h5>3rd Ventricle → Aqueduct of Sylvius</h5>Also called cerebral aqueduct</div>
      </div>
      <div class="flow-step">
        <div class="flow-num">4</div>
        <div class="flow-content"><h5>4th Ventricle → Foramina of Magendie &amp; Luschka</h5>Exit points to subarachnoid space</div>
      </div>
      <div class="flow-step">
        <div class="flow-num">5</div>
        <div class="flow-content"><h5>Subarachnoid Space → Arachnoid Villi</h5>Reabsorbed into superior sagittal sinus</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="callout yellow"><strong>⭐ Exam Pearl</strong> The cerebral aqueduct = Aqueduct of Sylvius (NOT the foramen of Monro, NOT the central canal). It connects the 3rd and 4th ventricles.</div>
</section>

