<section class="page-section anchor" id="three-ls">
  <div class="section-header">
    <span class="section-tag red">1.04</span>
    <h2 class="section-title">Principles of Localization — The 3 Ls</h2>
  </div>

  <div class="callout teal"><strong>Two Questions to Answer</strong> (1) WHERE is the lesion? → Anatomic Localization &nbsp;|&nbsp; (2) WHAT is the lesion? → Etiologic Diagnosis</div>

  <h3>⭐ Steps in Localization (Principle of Parsimony)</h3>
  <div class="algo">
    <div class="flow">
      <div class="flow-step"><div class="flow-num">1</div><div class="flow-content"><h5>Get All Clues</h5>History, PE, Neurologic PE — already forming a picture during history taking</div></div>
      <div class="flow-step"><div class="flow-num">2</div><div class="flow-content"><h5>List All Neurologic Problems</h5>Both subjective complaints AND objective findings; PE may be normal but patient feels otherwise</div></div>
      <div class="flow-step"><div class="flow-num">3</div><div class="flow-content"><h5>Determine Neuroanatomic Correlates</h5>Which anatomic areas explain each finding?</div></div>
      <div class="flow-step"><div class="flow-num red">4</div><div class="flow-content"><h5>⭐ Look for "Intersections" — Principle of Parsimony</h5>ONE single localization that accounts for ALL findings = the final localization (simplest explanation)</div></div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h3>⭐ Temporal Profile — Clue to Etiology</h3>
  <div class="tbl-wrap">
    <table>
      <tr><th>Time Course</th><th>Think of...</th></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl-red">Hyperacute (seconds–minutes)</td><td>Vascular: Ischemic stroke, intracerebral hemorrhage, SAH; Seizure</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl-red">Acute (hours–days)</td><td>Infection (bacterial meningitis, viral encephalitis), acute demyelinating, trauma</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">Subacute (weeks–months)</td><td>Fungal meningitis, TB meningitis, neoplasm (malignant), abscess</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">Chronic (years)</td><td>Neurodegenerative (Alzheimer's, Parkinson's), benign neoplasm, multiple sclerosis</td></tr>
    </table>
  </div>

  <h3>⭐ 3 Ls of Localization</h3>
  <div class="card-grid">
    <div class="card teal">
      <h4>1. LEVELIZE</h4>
      <ul>
        <li>Central vs Peripheral (CNS vs PNS)</li>
        <li>UMN vs LMN</li>
        <li>Supratentorial vs Infratentorial</li>
        <li>Brain vs Spinal Cord</li>
        <li>If brain → Cortex vs Brainstem</li>
        <li>If brainstem → Midbrain / Pons / Medulla</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="card teal">
      <h4>2. LATERALIZE</h4>
      <ul>
        <li>Left, Right, Both, Midline, or Generalized</li>
        <li>Hemispheric vs Brainstem (cross-deficit pattern)</li>
        <li>Look for cranial nerve involvement → ipsilateral to lesion</li>
        <li>Motor/sensory deficits → contralateral for cortical/SC</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="card teal">
      <h4>3. LOCALIZE</h4>
      <ul>
        <li>Find the specific area</li>
        <li>Cortical signs → frontal/parietal/temporal/occipital</li>
        <li>CN involvement identifies brainstem level</li>
        <li>Sensory level → spinal cord level</li>
        <li>Apply Principle of Parsimony</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- UMN vs LMN -->

<section class="page-section anchor" id="umn-lmn">
  <div class="section-header">
    <span class="section-tag red">1.04</span>
    <h2 class="section-title">UMN vs LMN & Corticospinal Tract</h2>
  </div>

  <div class="compare">
    <div class="compare-col">
      <div class="compare-col-head teal">Upper Motor Neuron (UMN)</div>
      <div class="compare-col-body">
        <ul>
          <li>Little or NO wasting</li>
          <li>↑ Tone — <strong>SPASTICITY</strong></li>
          <li>↑ Reflexes — <strong>HYPERREFLEXIA</strong> (+3/+4)</li>
          <li>(+) <strong>Babinski sign</strong></li>
          <li>(+) Hoffman sign</li>
          <li>Clonus may be present</li>
          <li>Involves larger muscle groups</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="compare-col">
      <div class="compare-col-head red">Lower Motor Neuron (LMN)</div>
      <div class="compare-col-body">
        <ul>
          <li>WASTING / Atrophy</li>
          <li>↓ Tone — <strong>FLACCIDITY</strong></li>
          <li>↓/Absent reflexes — <strong>HYPOREFLEXIA/AREFLEXIA</strong></li>
          <li><strong>FASCICULATIONS</strong></li>
          <li>No Babinski</li>
          <li>(−) Clonus</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="callout yellow"><strong>⭐ Exam Pearl</strong> Both UMN + LMN signs together = ALS (Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis) or spinal cord lesion. ALS: tongue fibrillations (LMN) + Babinski/hyperreflexia (UMN) + NORMAL SENSATION.</div>

  <h3>⭐ Levels Along the Corticospinal Tract</h3>
  <div class="tbl-wrap">
    <table>
      <tr><th>Level</th><th>Location</th><th>Presentation</th><th>Clue</th></tr>
      <tr><td rowspan="2" class="hl">Cortex</td><td>Cortical</td><td>Contralateral arm &amp; leg weakness + <strong>CORTICAL SIGNS</strong> (aphasia, gaze deviation)</td><td>Aphasia = cortex</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Subcortical (Corona radiata, Internal capsule)</td><td>Contralateral arm &amp; leg weakness; <strong>NO cortical signs</strong> = pure weakness</td><td>Internal capsule → pure motor stroke</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">Brainstem (Midbrain, Pons, Medulla rostral)</td><td>—</td><td>Contralateral arm &amp; leg weakness</td><td>Midbrain: CN III/IV; Pons: CN V/VI/VII/VIII; Medulla: CN IX/X/XI/XII</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl-red">Brainstem (Medulla caudal)</td><td>—</td><td><strong>IPSILATERAL</strong> arm &amp; leg weakness (decussation at pyramids)</td><td>Cross-deficit = brainstem lesion</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">Spinal Cord Medial</td><td>—</td><td>Upper extremity weakness</td><td>—</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">Spinal Cord Lateral</td><td>—</td><td>Lower extremity weakness</td><td>—</td></tr>
    </table>
  </div>

  <div class="callout red"><strong>⭐ Decussation Points (Must Memorize!)</strong><br>• Corticospinal Tract → Medulla (pyramidal decussation)<br>• Dorsal Column Medial Lemniscal → Lower Medulla<br>• Spinothalamic Tract → Anterior white commissure of SPINAL CORD (1–2 levels above entry)</div>

  <h3>⭐ Patterns of Weakness</h3>
  <div class="tbl-wrap">
    <table>
      <tr><th>Pattern</th><th>Localization</th><th>Key Feature</th></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">One side — face, arm, leg</td><td>Hemispheric lesion (cortex, internal capsule)</td><td>Cortical signs if cortex; pure weakness if internal capsule</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">Cross-deficit: face one side, body opposite</td><td><strong>Brainstem</strong></td><td>Highest ipsilateral CN identifies level (midbrain/pons/medulla)</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">Sensory level + bilateral weakness</td><td>Spinal cord</td><td>Band-like sensory loss; bowel/bladder issues</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">Root distribution</td><td>Root lesion</td><td>Dermatomal pattern; radicular pain</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">Glove-and-stocking</td><td>Polyneuropathy</td><td>Distal, symmetric; DM neuropathy</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">Proximal &gt; distal</td><td>Myopathy</td><td>Hip/shoulder girdle weakness</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">Fatigable ptosis + proximal weakness</td><td>NMJ (Myasthenia Gravis)</td><td>Ice pack test (+); worse at end of day; no atrophy/fasciculations</td></tr>
    </table>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- SPINAL CORD -->

<section class="page-section anchor" id="spinal-cord">
  <div class="section-header">
    <span class="section-tag red">1.04</span>
    <h2 class="section-title">Spinal Cord Tracts & Syndromes</h2>
  </div>

  <h3>⭐ Three Key Tracts (Location + Function + Side)</h3>
  <div class="tbl-wrap">
    <table>
      <tr><th>Tract</th><th>Location in SC</th><th>Function</th><th>Side of Effect</th><th>Decussation</th></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">Dorsal Column</td><td>Posterior SC (<em>"likod"</em> = back)</td><td>Fine touch, vibration, proprioception</td><td><strong>Ipsilateral</strong></td><td>Lower Medulla</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">Corticospinal Tract</td><td>Lateral SC</td><td>Motor</td><td><strong>Ipsilateral</strong> (below decussation)</td><td>Medulla (pyramids)</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">Spinothalamic Tract</td><td>Anterolateral SC</td><td>Pain &amp; temperature</td><td><strong>Contralateral</strong></td><td>Anterior white commissure of SC (1–2 levels above)</td></tr>
    </table>
  </div>

  <h3>⭐ Spinal Cord Syndromes</h3>
  <div class="tbl-wrap">
    <table>
      <tr><th>Syndrome</th><th>What's Hit</th><th>What's Lost</th><th>What's Spared</th><th>Classic Cause</th></tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="hl">Posterior Cord Syndrome</td>
        <td>Dorsal Columns</td>
        <td>Proprioception, vibration, fine touch → <strong>"stomping gait"</strong></td>
        <td>Motor strength, pain sensation</td>
        <td>B12 deficiency, syphilis</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="hl">Anterior Cord Syndrome</td>
        <td>Anterior horn, corticospinal, spinothalamic (spares dorsal column)</td>
        <td>Motor, pain &amp; temperature</td>
        <td>Fine touch, vibration, proprioception</td>
        <td>Anterior spinal artery infarct</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="hl" style="background:#fff3e0">Central Cord Syndrome ⭐</td>
        <td>Center of cord first</td>
        <td>UE &gt;&gt; LE weakness ("Man in a barrel")</td>
        <td>Sacral sensation often preserved</td>
        <td>Hyperextension injury (elderly)</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="hl" style="background:#fff3e0">Brown-Séquard Syndrome ⭐</td>
        <td>Half (hemi-section) of cord</td>
        <td><strong>Ipsilateral</strong>: motor (CST) + proprioception/vibration (DC); <strong>Contralateral</strong>: pain &amp; temp (ST)</td>
        <td>Varies</td>
        <td>Penetrating trauma, tumor</td>
      </tr>
    </table>
  </div>

  <div class="callout yellow"><strong>⭐ Brown-Séquard Memory Trick</strong> SAME side (ipsilateral) = Motor + Proprioception lost. OPPOSITE side (contralateral) = Pain + Temperature lost. "Split the cord, split the deficits."</div>

