<!-- CASE APPROACH -->

<section class="page-section anchor" id="cases">
  <div class="section-header">
    <span class="section-tag red">1.04</span>
    <h2 class="section-title">Case Approach — Putting It Together</h2>
  </div>

  <h3>Step-by-Step Localization Framework</h3>
  <div class="algo">
    <h4>⭐ How to Approach ANY Neuro Case</h4>
    <div class="flow">
      <div class="flow-step"><div class="flow-num">1</div><div class="flow-content"><h5>LEVELIZE: UMN vs LMN?</h5>UMN → spasticity, hyperreflexia, Babinski, no atrophy | LMN → flaccid, hypo/areflexia, atrophy, fasciculations | BOTH → ALS or spinal cord</div></div>
      <div class="flow-step"><div class="flow-num">2</div><div class="flow-content"><h5>LEVELIZE: Central (CNS) or Peripheral (PNS)?</h5>CNS → aphasia, gaze deviation, Babinski | PNS → glove-stocking pattern, dermatomal, NMJ features</div></div>
      <div class="flow-step"><div class="flow-num">3</div><div class="flow-content"><h5>LEVELIZE: Supratentorial vs Infratentorial?</h5>Aphasia → brain (cortex) | Cross-deficit + CN involvement → brainstem (infratentorial) | Sensory level → spinal cord</div></div>
      <div class="flow-step"><div class="flow-num">4</div><div class="flow-content"><h5>LATERALIZE: Which Side?</h5>Hemispheric: same side face + body | Brainstem: cross-deficit (face contralateral to body) | Gaze deviation: toward lesion (destructive)</div></div>
      <div class="flow-step"><div class="flow-num red">5</div><div class="flow-content"><h5>LOCALIZE: Specific Area</h5>Cortical signs (aphasia) → which lobe? | CN involved → which brainstem level? | Sensory level + Brown-Séquard pattern → spinal level</div></div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="callout yellow"><strong>⭐ Key Shortcuts</strong><br>
  • Gaze toward lesion (destructive) + right-sided weakness + aphasia → LEFT frontal/MCA stroke<br>
  • Left face (LMN, forehead affected) + right body weakness → LEFT Pons (CN VI/VII + CST)<br>
  • Ipsilateral ptosis + miosis + anhidrosis → Horner's (sympathetic disruption)<br>
  • Bilateral motor + bilateral sensory at umbilicus, dissociated → Spinal cord (Brown-Séquard at T10)<br>
  • UMN + LMN + NO sensory → ALS<br>
  • Fatigable ptosis, ice pack (+), proximal weakness → MG (NMJ)</div>

  <h3>Normal Pressure Hydrocephalus — Triad</h3>
  <div class="callout teal"><strong>Wobbly + Wacky + Wet</strong><br>
  • Wobbly = Gait disturbance (magnetic gait)<br>
  • Wacky = Cognitive impairment<br>
  • Wet = Impaired bladder control (urinary incontinence)</div>
</section>

