      <tr><th>Component</th><th>Max Pts</th><th>What to Test</th><th>High-Yield Notes</th></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">Orientation</td><td>10</td><td>Date, day, season, place, floor, street, municipality, city, country (5 time + 5 place)</td><td>Tagalog versions acceptable</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">Immediate Recall</td><td>3</td><td>"Mangga-Mesa-Pera" — 1 second interval</td><td><strong>Only FIRST attempt scored</strong>; allow up to 6 attempts but score only first</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">Attention</td><td>5</td><td>Serial 7s (100-7-7...) OR backward spelling "KARNE" or "WORLD"</td><td>Serial 7s = attention; 5 subtractions</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">Delayed Recall</td><td>3</td><td>Recall the 3 words from immediate recall; 10 secs per word</td><td>—</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">Language</td><td>9</td><td>Naming (2) + Repetition (1) + 3-step command (3) + Reading (1) + Writing (1) + Copying pentagons (1)</td><td>No ruler or cues for copying; command uses NONDOMINANT hand</td></tr>
    </table>
  </div>

  <h3>⭐ MoCA-P</h3>
  <div class="callout green"><strong>Cutoff: 24/30</strong> | More sensitive than MMSE for mild cognitive impairment | Education adjustments: (+2) for 4–9 years education, (+1) for 10–12 years education</div>

  <h3>Parietal Lobe Tests — Agnosia</h3>
  <div class="tbl-wrap">
    <table>
      <tr><th>Test</th><th>What it Tests</th><th>How to Test</th></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">Astereognosia</td><td>Loss of form sense</td><td>Eyes closed → identify coin/pen/key placed in palm</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">Agraphesthesia</td><td>Loss of graphic sense</td><td>Eyes closed → trace number/letter on palm with blunt tip</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">Atopognosia</td><td>Loss of cutaneous localization</td><td>Left angular gyrus area; cannot localize skin stimuli</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">Hemispatial Neglect ⭐</td><td>Right parietal lesion → LEFT side ignored</td><td>Draw clock — numbers crowded only on right; left side empty</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">Sensory Extinction</td><td>Inattention to bilateral stimulation</td><td>Touch both hands simultaneously → patient reports only one side</td></tr>
    </table>
  </div>

  <div class="callout yellow"><strong>Apraxia Types</strong><br>
  • Ideomotor: knows how but cannot perform on command (e.g., show me how to use scissors)<br>
  • Constructional: cannot copy geometric figures<br>
  • Dressing: cannot orient/put on clothes → <strong>Right parietal lesion</strong></div>
</section>

<!-- CN EXAM -->

<section class="page-section anchor" id="cn-exam">
  <div class="section-header">
    <span class="section-tag purple">1.03</span>
    <h2 class="section-title">Cranial Nerve Examination</h2>
  </div>

  <div class="tbl-wrap">
    <table>
      <tr><th>CN</th><th>Name</th><th>How to Test</th><th>⭐ High-Yield Findings</th></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">I</td><td>Olfactory</td><td>Coffee/vanilla (NOT alcohol/perfume); one nostril at a time; 2nd trial: withhold stimulus (tests suggestibility)</td><td>Anosmia; do NOT use strong scents (activates CN V)</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">II</td><td>Optic</td><td>Snellen/Jaeger chart; confrontation testing; Ishihara (color); fundoscopy</td><td>Loss of venous pulsation on fundoscopy → ↑ICP; papilledema</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">II/III</td><td>Optic/Oculomotor</td><td>Pupillary light reflex; swinging flashlight (RAPD); convergence/miosis; accommodation</td><td>RAPD: opposite eye dilates when light shone; CN III palsy = blown pupil</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">III,IV,VI</td><td>Oculomotor, Trochlear, Abducens</td><td>H-pattern EOM testing; Hirschberg test (corneal light reflection)</td><td>CN VI = lateral rectus (abduction); CN IV = superior oblique (only CN exiting dorsally); CN III = all others + pupil</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">V</td><td>Trigeminal</td><td>Sensory: cotton to V1/V2/V3 divisions; Motor: palpate masseter during clench; jaw opening against resistance</td><td>V1=ophthalmic, V2=maxillary, V3=mandibular; masseter = V3 motor</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">V+VII</td><td>Trigem + Facial</td><td>Corneal reflex: touch lateral cornea with fine cotton; approach from side (avoid visual field)</td><td>Afferent = CN V; Efferent = CN VII; used in comatose patients</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">VII</td><td>Facial</td><td>Frontalis (wrinkle forehead); Orbicularis oculi (close eyes tight); Buccinator (smile/nasolabial fold); Platysma (pull corners down)</td><td>Peripheral (Bell's Palsy): ENTIRE face ipsilateral (forehead involved). Central UMN: LOWER face only (forehead SPARED due to bilateral cortical innervation)</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">VIII</td><td>Vestibulocochlear</td><td>Whispered voice; Weber test (tuning fork on forehead); Rinne test (mastoid vs air)</td><td>Weber lateralizes to AFFECTED ear in conductive loss; to NORMAL ear in sensorineural. Rinne: AC&gt;BC = normal; BC≥AC = conductive; AC&gt;BC both diminished = sensorineural</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">IX/X</td><td>Glossopharyngeal/Vagus</td><td>KLM test (Ka=palate/CN X; La=tongue/CN XII; Ma=lips/CN VII); palate elevation ("Ahh"); gag reflex; uvula position</td><td>Uvula deviates AWAY from affected side (toward functioning side). Absent gag: IX afferent or X efferent lesion</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">XI</td><td>Spinal Accessory</td><td>Head turn against resistance (tests contralateral SCM); shoulder shrug (trapezius)</td><td>Head turned LEFT = tests RIGHT SCM; ipsilateral CN XI lesion if weak</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">XII</td><td>Hypoglossal</td><td>Inspect tongue for hemiatrophy; protrude tongue; side-to-side movement</td><td>Tongue deviates TOWARD the side of the lesion (ipsilateral); hemiatrophy = most reliable sign</td></tr>
    </table>
  </div>

  <div class="callout yellow"><strong>⭐ Facial Nerve Pearl</strong> Upper face (forehead) has bilateral cortical innervation. Lower face has only contralateral. So: <br>• <strong>Peripheral CN VII</strong> (Bell's palsy): forehead INVOLVED, entire face ipsilateral<br>• <strong>Central UMN</strong> lesion: forehead SPARED, only lower contralateral face weak</div>
</section>

<!-- MOTOR & REFLEX -->

<section class="page-section anchor" id="motor-exam">
  <div class="section-header">
    <span class="section-tag purple">1.03</span>
    <h2 class="section-title">Motor, Reflex & Sensory Examination</h2>
  </div>

  <h3>⭐ Muscle Strength Grading (MRC Scale)</h3>
  <div class="tbl-wrap">
    <table>
      <tr><th>Grade</th><th>Meaning</th></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">5</td><td>Normal strength — full range, full resistance</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">4</td><td>Full range against gravity + some resistance</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">3</td><td>Full range against gravity, NO additional resistance</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">2</td><td>Moves only when gravity eliminated</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">1</td><td>Flicker of contraction; no movement</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">0</td><td>Complete paralysis</td></tr>
    </table>
  </div>

  <h3>⭐ Deep Tendon Reflex Grading</h3>
  <div class="tbl-wrap">
    <table>
      <tr><th>Grade</th><th>Meaning</th><th>Clinical Significance</th></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">0</td><td>Areflexia</td><td>LMN lesion, peripheral neuropathy</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">1</td><td>Hyporeflexia</td><td>LMN, early peripheral neuropathy</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">2</td><td>Normal</td><td>—</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">3</td><td>Hyperreflexia</td><td>UMN lesion</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">4</td><td>Clonus present</td><td><strong>Definite UMN lesion</strong></td></tr>
    </table>
  </div>

  <h3>DTR Testing & Root Levels</h3>
  <div class="tbl-wrap">
    <table>
      <tr><th>Reflex</th><th>Root Level</th><th>How to Elicit</th></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">Biceps</td><td>C5–C6</td><td>Examiner's thumb on biceps tendon → strike thumb</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">Triceps</td><td>C7–C8</td><td>Strike triceps tendon above olecranon</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">Brachioradialis</td><td>C5–C6</td><td>Strike radial styloid; strike examiner's thumb not bone</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">Patellar</td><td>L3–L4</td><td>Strike patellar tendon; most commonly tested</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">Achilles</td><td>S1</td><td>Strike Achilles tendon; absent = S1 lesion</td></tr>
    </table>
  </div>

  <h3>⭐ Primitive Reflexes (UMN Signs)</h3>
  <div class="tbl-wrap">
    <table>
      <tr><th>Reflex</th><th>How to Elicit</th><th>Positive Response</th><th>Significance</th></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">Babinski</td><td>Stroke lateral sole from heel → base of toes medially</td><td>Dorsiflexion of big toe (± fanning of toes)</td><td>UMN lesion; normal in infants (plantar grasp); afferent S1, efferent L5-S1</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">Tromner's</td><td>Briskly flip distal phalanx UPWARD</td><td>Flexion of fingers and thumb</td><td>UMN lesion</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">Hoffman's</td><td>Flick/depress distal phalanx DOWNWARD; let it flip up</td><td>Thumb/finger flexion</td><td>UMN; upper limb Babinski equivalent</td></tr>
    </table>
  </div>

  <h3>Superficial Reflexes</h3>
  <div class="tbl-wrap">
    <table>
      <tr><th>Reflex</th><th>Root</th><th>How</th><th>Clinical Use</th></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">Abdominal</td><td>T8–T12</td><td>Stroke toward umbilicus → umbilicus moves toward stimulus</td><td>Localizes thoracic cord lesions</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">Cremasteric</td><td>L1–L2</td><td>Stroke medial inner thigh → testis elevates</td><td>Absent in testicular torsion</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">Anal Wink</td><td>S2–S4</td><td>Prick perianal skin → sphincter constriction</td><td><strong>First reflex to return after spinal shock</strong></td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">Bulbocavernosus</td><td>S3–S4</td><td>Squeeze glans → anal contraction detected by finger</td><td>Tests sacral sparing</td></tr>
    </table>
  </div>

  <h3>Cerebellar Examination</h3>
  <div class="tbl-wrap">
    <table>
      <tr><th>Test</th><th>Positive Finding</th><th>Significance</th></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">Finger-to-Nose</td><td>Intention tremor (↑ as approaches target); dysmetria (over/undershoot)</td><td>Cerebellar dysfunction</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">Dysdiadochokinesia</td><td>Slow, irregular, clumsy alternating movements (pronation/supination)</td><td>Cerebellar</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">Heel-to-Shin</td><td>Wobbly, misses shin</td><td>Lower limb cerebellar</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">Romberg's Test</td><td>Loses balance when eyes closed (positive = falls)</td><td><strong>NOT cerebellar</strong>; tests dorsal column/proprioception; also vestibular disease</td></tr>
    </table>
  </div>

  <div class="callout red"><strong>⭐ Romberg's Pearl</strong> Romberg test = tests PROPRIOCEPTION (dorsal column), NOT cerebellar function. Cerebellar ataxia is present even with eyes OPEN (doesn't significantly worsen with eye closure).</div>

  <h3>Sensory Modalities</h3>
  <div class="tbl-wrap">
    <table>
      <tr><th>Modality</th><th>Pathway</th><th>How to Test</th></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">Fine touch, vibration, proprioception</td><td>Dorsal Column → ipsilateral</td><td>Cotton wisp; tuning fork on DIP joint; grasp 4th digit, move up/down</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">Pain &amp; temperature</td><td>Spinothalamic → contralateral</td><td>Toothpick (sharp/dull); warm/cold tubes; tuning fork (cold) vs finger (warm)</td></tr>
    </table>
  </div>

  <h3>Gait Examination</h3>
  <div class="tbl-wrap">
    <table>
      <tr><th>Gait Type</th><th>Characteristics</th><th>Localization</th></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">Parkinsonian</td><td>Shuffling steps, decreased arm swing (often unilateral), festination, incomplete foot clearance, turns en bloc</td><td>Basal ganglia (extrapyramidal)</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">Wide-based / Ataxic</td><td>Unsteady, wide base, swaying</td><td>Cerebellar</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">Magnetic / Frontal</td><td>Feet "stuck to floor," difficulty initiating, normal power</td><td>Frontal lobe (NPH)</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">Steppage</td><td>High stepping; foot drop; slap gait</td><td>Foot dorsiflexor weakness (L4-L5)</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">Stomping</td><td>High-stepping, stamps foot; cannot sense position</td><td>Dorsal column (proprioception loss)</td></tr>
    </table>
  </div>

  <h3>⭐ Meningeal Signs</h3>
  <div class="tbl-wrap">
    <table>
      <tr><th>Sign</th><th>How to Test (PASSIVE — examiner does the movement)</th><th>Positive Finding</th><th>Memory</th></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">Brudzinski</td><td>Patient supine; examiner passively flexes neck</td><td>Involuntary hip &amp; knee flexion</td><td><strong>B</strong>rudzinski = <strong>B</strong>atok (neck)</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">Kernig</td><td>Patient supine; flex hip and knee to 90°; passively extend knee</td><td>Pain/resistance at >135° extension</td><td><strong>K</strong>ernig = <strong>K</strong>er-<strong>knee</strong></td></tr>
    </table>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- COMATOSE -->

<section class="page-section anchor" id="comatose">
  <div class="section-header">
    <span class="section-tag purple">1.03</span>
    <h2 class="section-title">Examination of the Comatose Patient</h2>
  </div>

  <h3>⭐ Respiration → Localization</h3>
  <div class="tbl-wrap">
    <table>
      <tr><th>Breathing Pattern</th><th>Lesion Location</th><th>Description</th></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">Sighing/yawning</td><td>Upper Diencephalon</td><td>Non-specific; early cortical dysfunction</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl-red">Cheyne-Stokes ⭐</td><td>Lower Diencephalon / Forebrain</td><td>Crescendo-decrescendo hyperpnea alternating with apnea; often due to metabolic or bilateral cortical dysfunction</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">Hyperventilation</td><td>Midbrain</td><td>Rapid, deep, sustained breathing</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">Apneustic</td><td>Rostral Pons</td><td>Prolonged inspiratory pause</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl">Ataxic Breathing</td><td>Lower Pons</td><td>Completely irregular, unpredictable</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="hl-red">Respiratory Arrest</td><td>Upper Medulla</td><td>Ataxic → Apnea</td></tr>
    </table>
  </div>

  <h3>⭐ Caloric Testing — COWS Mnemonic</h3>
  <div class="mnemonic">
    <div class="mnemonic-label">Mnemonic — COWS</div>
    <div class="mnemonic-text">Cold → Opposite | Warm → Same</div>
    <div class="mnemonic-expand">Cold water in one ear → eyes move to OPPOSITE side (normal). Warm water → eyes move to SAME side. Absent response → brainstem dysfunction. Always check tympanic membrane first (intact needed)!</div>
  </div>

  <h3>Glasgow Coma Scale</h3>
  <div class="tbl-wrap">
    <table>
      <tr><th colspan="2">Eye Opening (1–4)</th><th colspan="2">Best Verbal (1–5)</th><th colspan="2">Best Motor (1–6)</th></tr>
      <tr><td>4</td><td>Spontaneous</td><td>5</td><td>Oriented</td><td>6</td><td>Obeys</td></tr>
      <tr><td>3</td><td>To speech</td><td>4</td><td>Confused</td><td>5</td><td>Localizes</td></tr>
      <tr><td>2</td><td>To pain</td><td>3</td><td>Inappropriate</td><td>4</td><td>Withdrawal</td></tr>
      <tr><td>1</td><td>None</td><td>2</td><td>Incomprehensible</td><td>3</td><td>Flexion (decorticate)</td></tr>
      <tr><td></td><td></td><td>1</td><td>None</td><td>2</td><td>Extension (decerebrate)</td></tr>
      <tr><td></td><td></td><td></td><td></td><td>1</td><td>None</td></tr>
    </table>
  </div>

  <div class="callout blue"><strong>Range</strong> Min = 3, Max = 15. GCS ≤8 = coma (intubation threshold).</div>

  <h3>⭐ Motor Posturing — Localization</h3>
  <div class="compare">
    <div class="compare-col">
      <div class="compare-col-head teal">Decorticate Posturing</div>
      <div class="compare-col-body">
        <ul>
          <li>Lesion ABOVE red nucleus (cortex/internal capsule)</li>
          <li>Arms FLEXED, legs extended</li>
          <li>Hands clasped to chest</li>
          <li>Less severe than decerebrate</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="compare-col">
      <div class="compare-col-head red">Decerebrate Posturing</div>
      <div class="compare-col-body">
        <ul>
          <li>Lesion BELOW red nucleus (midbrain/upper pons)</li>
          <li>Arms AND legs EXTENDED</li>
          <li>Forearms pronated</li>
          <li>More severe; worse prognosis</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

