<section class="page-section anchor" id="buzzwords">
  <div class="section-header">
    <span class="section-tag green">Quick Reference</span>
    <h2 class="section-title">Buzzwords & Must-Know Facts</h2>
  </div>

  <div class="bz-grid">
    <div class="bz-item"><div class="bz-term">Betz cells</div><div class="bz-def">Layer V of cortex; large pyramidal neurons → corticospinal tract → motor output</div></div>
    <div class="bz-item"><div class="bz-term">Neuron Doctrine</div><div class="bz-def">Cajal: neurons = separate cells; synapse between them; neuron = functional unit of brain</div></div>
    <div class="bz-item"><div class="bz-term">Saltatory conduction</div><div class="bz-def">Rapid nerve conduction via Nodes of Ranvier (jumps between gaps in myelin)</div></div>
    <div class="bz-item"><div class="bz-term">Golgi stain</div><div class="bz-def">Silver-staining technique developed by Camillo Golgi; used by Cajal to prove neuron doctrine</div></div>
    <div class="bz-item"><div class="bz-term">Monro-Kellie Doctrine</div><div class="bz-def">Cranial cavity = fixed volume; brain + blood + CSF; change in one affects others → ICP</div></div>
    <div class="bz-item"><div class="bz-term">~500 cc CSF/day</div><div class="bz-def">Produced by choroid plexus in ependymal cells; continuously reabsorbed</div></div>
    <div class="bz-item"><div class="bz-term">Principle of Parsimony</div><div class="bz-def">One lesion to explain ALL neurologic findings = simplest & best localization</div></div>
    <div class="bz-item"><div class="bz-term">Pie in the sky</div><div class="bz-def">Superior quadrantanopia = inferior (temporal) optic radiation (Meyer's loop) lesion</div></div>
    <div class="bz-item"><div class="bz-term">Pie on the floor</div><div class="bz-def">Inferior quadrantanopia = superior (parietal) optic radiation lesion</div></div>
    <div class="bz-item"><div class="bz-term">Macular sparing</div><div class="bz-def">Occipital lobe (PCA) lesion → homonymous hemianopia but central vision preserved; MCA also supplies macula</div></div>
    <div class="bz-item"><div class="bz-term">Tunnel vision</div><div class="bz-def">Bitemporal hemianopia = optic chiasm lesion (nasal fibers cross; temporal fields lost)</div></div>
    <div class="bz-item"><div class="bz-term">Word salad</div><div class="bz-def">Wernicke's aphasia: fluent, meaningless, jargon-filled speech; poor comprehension</div></div>
    <div class="bz-item"><div class="bz-term">Telegraphic speech</div><div class="bz-def">Broca's aphasia: non-fluent, 2-word sentences; can understand; frustration evident</div></div>
    <div class="bz-item"><div class="bz-term">Man in a barrel</div><div class="bz-def">Central cord syndrome: UE >> LE weakness; center of cord affected first</div></div>
    <div class="bz-item"><div class="bz-term">Split deficit</div><div class="bz-def">Brown-Séquard: ipsilateral motor/proprioception lost; contralateral pain/temp lost</div></div>
    <div class="bz-item"><div class="bz-term">Cross-deficit</div><div class="bz-def">Ipsilateral CN palsy + contralateral body weakness = BRAINSTEM lesion</div></div>
    <div class="bz-item"><div class="bz-term">Blown pupil</div><div class="bz-def">Dilated, fixed pupil = CN III palsy from uncal herniation; ↑ICP emergency</div></div>
    <div class="bz-item"><div class="bz-term">Pinpoint pupils</div><div class="bz-def">Pons lesion; bilateral sympathetic fiber disruption</div></div>
    <div class="bz-item"><div class="bz-term">Ice pack test</div><div class="bz-def">Ptosis improves with ice pack = Myasthenia Gravis; NMJ disorder</div></div>
    <div class="bz-item"><div class="bz-term">Wobbly-Wacky-Wet</div><div class="bz-def">Normal Pressure Hydrocephalus triad: gait disturbance + dementia + urinary incontinence</div></div>
    <div class="bz-item"><div class="bz-term">Cheyne-Stokes</div><div class="bz-def">Lower diencephalon/forebrain lesion; crescendo-decrescendo breathing → apnea cycles</div></div>
    <div class="bz-item"><div class="bz-term">RAPD</div><div class="bz-def">Relative Afferent Pupillary Defect: opposite eye dilates when light swung to affected eye (swinging flashlight test)</div></div>
    <div class="bz-item"><div class="bz-term">Acalculia + Agraphia</div><div class="bz-def">Both localise to LEFT parietal lobe, angular gyrus</div></div>
    <div class="bz-item"><div class="bz-term">Glove-and-stocking</div><div class="bz-def">Polyneuropathy pattern; distal, symmetric sensory loss; DM neuropathy</div></div>
    <div class="bz-item"><div class="bz-term">Uvula deviation</div><div class="bz-def">Deviates AWAY from affected CN X side (toward functioning side)</div></div>
    <div class="bz-item"><div class="bz-term">Tongue deviation</div><div class="bz-def">Deviates TOWARD side of CN XII lesion (ipsilateral)</div></div>
    <div class="bz-item"><div class="bz-term">Weber lateralization</div><div class="bz-def">Conductive loss: louder in AFFECTED ear. Sensorineural: louder in NORMAL ear</div></div>
    <div class="bz-item"><div class="bz-term">Anal wink first</div><div class="bz-def">First spinal reflex to return after spinal shock (S2-S4)</div></div>
    <div class="bz-item"><div class="bz-term">CN IV — dorsal exit</div><div class="bz-def">Trochlear nerve = ONLY cranial nerve to exit dorsally from brainstem; superior oblique muscle</div></div>
    <div class="bz-item"><div class="bz-term">~86 billion neurons</div><div class="bz-def">Average neuron count; each has ~7,000 synapses; brain ~2% of body weight (1200–1500g)</div></div>
  </div>
</section>

