<!-- Q2 -->
<div class="mcq" id="q2">
  <div class="mcq-num">Question 2</div>
  <div class="mcq-q">A patient presents with fluent speech, impaired comprehension, and impaired repetition. Where is the most likely lesion?</div>
  <div class="mcq-opts">
    <div class="mcq-opt" onclick="answer(this,'q2',false)"><span class="letter">A</span> Left posterior inferior frontal operculum (Broca's area)</div>
    <div class="mcq-opt" onclick="answer(this,'q2',false)"><span class="letter">B</span> Entire perisylvian area</div>
    <div class="mcq-opt" onclick="answer(this,'q2',true)"><span class="letter">C</span> Posterior perisylvian, temporal operculum (Wernicke's area)</div>
    <div class="mcq-opt" onclick="answer(this,'q2',false)"><span class="letter">D</span> Angular gyrus</div>
  </div>
  <div class="mcq-explain" id="q2-exp">Fluent + poor comprehension + poor repetition = Wernicke's aphasia. Location: posterior perisylvian/temporal operculum. Remember: Broca's = non-fluent; Anomic = fluent, comprehends, can repeat but poor naming; Global = all three impaired.</div>
</div>

<!-- Q3 -->
<div class="mcq" id="q3">
  <div class="mcq-num">Question 3</div>
  <div class="mcq-q">A 72-year-old man has sudden right-sided body weakness. He is drowsy, gaze is deviated to the LEFT, right face sags but he can raise BOTH eyebrows. DTRs +++, (+) Babinski on the right. Where is the lesion?</div>
  <div class="mcq-opts">
    <div class="mcq-opt" onclick="answer(this,'q3',false)"><span class="letter">A</span> Right frontoparietal cortex</div>
    <div class="mcq-opt" onclick="answer(this,'q3',true)"><span class="letter">B</span> Left frontoparietal cortex</div>
    <div class="mcq-opt" onclick="answer(this,'q3',false)"><span class="letter">C</span> Left pons</div>
    <div class="mcq-opt" onclick="answer(this,'q3',false)"><span class="letter">D</span> Right pons</div>
  </div>
  <div class="mcq-explain" id="q3-exp">Gaze deviated to LEFT = destructive lesion → FEF on the LEFT (eyes look toward the lesion). Right-sided body weakness = left hemisphere lesion (CST decussates). Bilateral eyebrow sparing = UMN (central) facial palsy. Right-sided hyperreflexia + Babinski confirms UMN. FINAL: Left frontoparietal cortex (MCA territory).</div>
</div>

<!-- Q4 -->
<div class="mcq" id="q4">
  <div class="mcq-num">Question 4</div>
  <div class="mcq-q">A patient has loss of pain and temperature on the LEFT body below T10, AND loss of motor function + proprioception/vibration on the RIGHT leg. What is the diagnosis?</div>
  <div class="mcq-opts">
    <div class="mcq-opt" onclick="answer(this,'q4',false)"><span class="letter">A</span> Anterior cord syndrome</div>
    <div class="mcq-opt" onclick="answer(this,'q4',false)"><span class="letter">B</span> Central cord syndrome</div>
    <div class="mcq-opt" onclick="answer(this,'q4',true)"><span class="letter">C</span> Brown-Séquard syndrome (right hemisection at T10)</div>
    <div class="mcq-opt" onclick="answer(this,'q4',false)"><span class="letter">D</span> Posterior cord syndrome</div>
  </div>
  <div class="mcq-explain" id="q4-exp">Brown-Séquard = spinal cord HEMISECTION. RIGHT side hemisection: IPSILATERAL (right) motor + proprioception/vibration lost (CST + dorsal column don't cross until medulla). CONTRALATERAL (left) pain/temp lost (spinothalamic crosses in cord at 1–2 levels above entry). "Split the cord, split the deficits."</div>
</div>

<!-- Q5 -->
<div class="mcq" id="q5">
  <div class="mcq-num">Question 5</div>
  <div class="mcq-q">A patient with bitemporal hemianopia (tunnel vision) most likely has a lesion at which structure?</div>
  <div class="mcq-opts">
    <div class="mcq-opt" onclick="answer(this,'q5',false)"><span class="letter">A</span> Right optic nerve</div>
    <div class="mcq-opt" onclick="answer(this,'q5',true)"><span class="letter">B</span> Optic chiasm</div>
    <div class="mcq-opt" onclick="answer(this,'q5',false)"><span class="letter">C</span> Left optic tract</div>
    <div class="mcq-opt" onclick="answer(this,'q5',false)"><span class="letter">D</span> Right occipital lobe</div>
  </div>
  <div class="mcq-explain" id="q5-exp">Bitemporal hemianopia (loss of peripheral temporal fields both eyes = "tunnel vision") = optic chiasm lesion. The nasal retinal fibers from both eyes cross at the chiasm — damage here knocks out both temporal visual fields. Classic cause: pituitary adenoma compressing from below.</div>
</div>

<!-- Q6 -->
<div class="mcq" id="q6">
  <div class="mcq-num">Question 6</div>
  <div class="mcq-q">A 54-year-old male has progressive weakness, tongue atrophy with fibrillations, bilateral hyperreflexia, and bilateral Babinski. Sensory examination is NORMAL. What is the most likely diagnosis?</div>
  <div class="mcq-opts">
    <div class="mcq-opt" onclick="answer(this,'q6',false)"><span class="letter">A</span> Myasthenia Gravis</div>
    <div class="mcq-opt" onclick="answer(this,'q6',false)"><span class="letter">B</span> Brown-Séquard Syndrome</div>
    <div class="mcq-opt" onclick="answer(this,'q6',true)"><span class="letter">C</span> Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis (ALS)</div>
    <div class="mcq-opt" onclick="answer(this,'q6',false)"><span class="letter">D</span> Guillain-Barré Syndrome</div>
  </div>
  <div class="mcq-explain" id="q6-exp">ALS = simultaneous UMN signs (hyperreflexia, Babinski) + LMN signs (tongue atrophy, fibrillations/fasciculations, muscle atrophy) with PRESERVED SENSATION. This is pathognomonic. MG = NMJ (fatigable, no UMN signs). GBS = ascending flaccid paralysis with areflexia. Brown-Séquard = sensory deficits present.</div>
</div>

<!-- Q7 -->
<div class="mcq" id="q7">
  <div class="mcq-num">Question 7</div>
  <div class="mcq-q">Which glial cell is responsible for waste clearance from the brain and plays a role in CSF homeostasis?</div>
  <div class="mcq-opts">
    <div class="mcq-opt" onclick="answer(this,'q7',false)"><span class="letter">A</span> Astrocytes</div>
    <div class="mcq-opt" onclick="answer(this,'q7',true)"><span class="letter">B</span> Ependymal cells</div>
    <div class="mcq-opt" onclick="answer(this,'q7',false)"><span class="letter">C</span> Oligodendrocytes</div>
    <div class="mcq-opt" onclick="answer(this,'q7',false)"><span class="letter">D</span> Microglia</div>
  </div>
  <div class="mcq-explain" id="q7-exp">Ependymal cells line the ventricles; they produce CSF via the choroid plexus and are responsible for waste clearance and brain metabolism. Astrocytes provide nourishment (different function). Oligodendrocytes = myelin in CNS. Microglia = immune/scavenger.</div>
</div>

<!-- Q8 -->
<div class="mcq" id="q8">
  <div class="mcq-num">Question 8</div>
  <div class="mcq-q">A comatose patient has PINPOINT pupils. Where is the most likely lesion?</div>
  <div class="mcq-opts">
    <div class="mcq-opt" onclick="answer(this,'q8',false)"><span class="letter">A</span> Midbrain</div>
    <div class="mcq-opt" onclick="answer(this,'q8',false)"><span class="letter">B</span> Diencephalon</div>
    <div class="mcq-opt" onclick="answer(this,'q8',true)"><span class="letter">C</span> Pons</div>
    <div class="mcq-opt" onclick="answer(this,'q8',false)"><span class="letter">D</span> CN III (uncal herniation)</div>
  </div>
  <div class="mcq-explain" id="q8-exp">Pinpoint pupils = PONS lesion. Mnemonic: Pin-PONT-ine → Pinpoint. This occurs due to bilateral disruption of descending sympathetic fibers in the pons. Midbrain = mid-position fixed pupils. CN III/uncal herniation = dilated fixed (blown) pupil. Diencephalon = small reactive pupils.</div>
</div>

<!-- Q9 -->
<div class="mcq" id="q9">
  <div class="mcq-num">Question 9</div>
  <div class="mcq-q">A patient has ipsilateral oculomotor palsy (CN III) AND contralateral hemiplegia. What brainstem syndrome is this, and at what level?</div>
  <div class="mcq-opts">
    <div class="mcq-opt" onclick="answer(this,'q9',false)"><span class="letter">A</span> Wallenberg syndrome; lateral medulla</div>
    <div class="mcq-opt" onclick="answer(this,'q9',false)"><span class="letter">B</span> Medial medullary syndrome; medial medulla</div>
    <div class="mcq-opt" onclick="answer(this,'q9',true)"><span class="letter">C</span> Weber syndrome; midbrain (ventromedial)</div>
    <div class="mcq-opt" onclick="answer(this,'q9',false)"><span class="letter">D</span> Millard-Gubler syndrome; pons</div>
  </div>
  <div class="mcq-explain" id="q9-exp">Weber syndrome = midbrain (ventromedial) lesion affecting CN III nucleus/fascicles + corticospinal tract. Ipsilateral CN III palsy (ptosis, dilated pupil, eye down and out) + contralateral hemiplegia. CN III is in the MIDBRAIN. Millard-Gubler = pons (CN VI + VII + contralateral hemiplegia).</div>
</div>

<!-- Q10 -->
<div class="mcq" id="q10">
  <div class="mcq-num">Question 10</div>
  <div class="mcq-q">A 28-year-old woman has fatigable ptosis that is WORSE at the end of the day and IMPROVES with ice pack application. Proximal muscle weakness is noted bilaterally. Sensory exam and reflexes are normal. What is the most likely diagnosis?</div>
  <div class="mcq-opts">
    <div class="mcq-opt" onclick="answer(this,'q10',false)"><span class="letter">A</span> Horner's syndrome</div>
    <div class="mcq-opt" onclick="answer(this,'q10',false)"><span class="letter">B</span> Polymyositis</div>
    <div class="mcq-opt" onclick="answer(this,'q10',true)"><span class="letter">C</span> Myasthenia Gravis (NMJ disorder)</div>
    <div class="mcq-opt" onclick="answer(this,'q10',false)"><span class="letter">D</span> CN III palsy from aneurysm</div>
  </div>
  <div class="mcq-explain" id="q10-exp">Myasthenia Gravis hallmarks: (1) Fatigable weakness — worse at end of day; (2) Ice pack test positive (cold improves NMJ transmission); (3) Ptosis and diplopia common; (4) Proximal > distal weakness; (5) No atrophy or fasciculations; (6) Normal reflexes and sensation. NMJ = post-synaptic acetylcholine receptor antibodies.</div>
</div>

<!-- Q11 -->
<div class="mcq" id="q11">
  <div class="mcq-num">Question 11</div>
  <div class="mcq-q">Which CSF pathway structure directly connects the 3rd ventricle to the 4th ventricle?</div>
  <div class="mcq-opts">
    <div class="mcq-opt" onclick="answer(this,'q11',false)"><span class="letter">A</span> Foramen of Monro</div>
    <div class="mcq-opt" onclick="answer(this,'q11',false)"><span class="letter">B</span> Foramen of Magendie</div>
    <div class="mcq-opt" onclick="answer(this,'q11',true)"><span class="letter">C</span> Aqueduct of Sylvius (cerebral aqueduct)</div>
    <div class="mcq-opt" onclick="answer(this,'q11',false)"><span class="letter">D</span> Central canal</div>
  </div>
  <div class="mcq-explain" id="q11-exp">Aqueduct of Sylvius (cerebral aqueduct) connects the 3rd ventricle to the 4th ventricle. Foramen of Monro = lateral ventricles → 3rd ventricle. Foramen of Magendie + Luschka = 4th ventricle → subarachnoid space. Central canal = inferior drainage from 4th ventricle into spinal cord.</div>
</div>

<!-- Q12 -->
<div class="mcq" id="q12">
  <div class="mcq-num">Question 12</div>
  <div class="mcq-q">A patient is asked to perform the MMSE. On immediate recall, they get 2 words correct on the 1st attempt, then all 3 on the 2nd attempt. What is the immediate recall score?</div>
  <div class="mcq-opts">
    <div class="mcq-opt" onclick="answer(this,'q12',false)"><span class="letter">A</span> 3/3</div>
    <div class="mcq-opt" onclick="answer(this,'q12',true)"><span class="letter">B</span> 2/3</div>
    <div class="mcq-opt" onclick="answer(this,'q12',false)"><span class="letter">C</span> 0/3 (need to redo)</div>
    <div class="mcq-opt" onclick="answer(this,'q12',false)"><span class="letter">D</span> Average of all attempts</div>
  </div>
  <div class="mcq-explain" id="q12-exp">Only the FIRST attempt is scored in MMSE immediate recall! Even if the patient gets all 3 on subsequent attempts (up to 6 attempts allowed), only the 1st repetition determines the score. Answer = 2/3.</div>
</div>

<!-- Q13 -->
<div class="mcq" id="q13">
  <div class="mcq-num">Question 13</div>
  <div class="mcq-q">A 72-year-old man presents with right arm > leg weakness with sudden onset. His leg is relatively spared compared to his arm and face. Which artery is most likely occluded?</div>
  <div class="mcq-opts">
    <div class="mcq-opt" onclick="answer(this,'q13',false)"><span class="letter">A</span> Right Anterior Cerebral Artery (ACA)</div>
    <div class="mcq-opt" onclick="answer(this,'q13',true)"><span class="letter">B</span> Left Middle Cerebral Artery (MCA)</div>
    <div class="mcq-opt" onclick="answer(this,'q13',false)"><span class="letter">C</span> Left Posterior Cerebral Artery (PCA)</div>
    <div class="mcq-opt" onclick="answer(this,'q13',false)"><span class="letter">D</span> Left Anterior Cerebral Artery (ACA)</div>
  </div>
  <div class="mcq-explain" id="q13-exp">MCA supplies face and arm motor/sensory cortex (lateral brain). ACA supplies leg motor/sensory cortex (medial brain). Face + arm > leg → MCA territory. Right-sided weakness → LEFT hemisphere lesion. PCA = visual cortex/thalamus. Left MCA infarct = most common stroke causing arm/face > leg weakness ± aphasia (if dominant hemisphere).</div>
</div>

<!-- Q14 -->
<div class="mcq" id="q14">
  <div class="mcq-num">Question 14</div>
  <div class="mcq-q">On the Rinne test, bone conduction (BC) is equal to or greater than air conduction (AC). What does this indicate?</div>
  <div class="mcq-opts">
    <div class="mcq-opt" onclick="answer(this,'q14',false)"><span class="letter">A</span> Normal hearing</div>
    <div class="mcq-opt" onclick="answer(this,'q14',true)"><span class="letter">B</span> Conductive hearing loss</div>
    <div class="mcq-opt" onclick="answer(this,'q14',false)"><span class="letter">C</span> Sensorineural hearing loss</div>
    <div class="mcq-opt" onclick="answer(this,'q14',false)"><span class="letter">D</span> Mixed hearing loss</div>
  </div>
  <div class="mcq-explain" id="q14-exp">Normal (Positive Rinne): AC > BC. Conductive hearing loss: BC ≥ AC (sound from bone lasts as long or longer than air because the air-conduction pathway is blocked; bone vibrations bypass the obstruction). Sensorineural: AC > BC but both are diminished vs. normal. Examples of conductive: otitis media, cerumen impaction, otosclerosis.</div>
</div>

