<div class="mcq" id="q15">
  <div class="mcq-num">Question 15</div>
  <div class="mcq-q">A patient has triad of MIOSIS, PTOSIS, and ANHIDROSIS on the right side of the face. What is the diagnosis and which system is disrupted?</div>
  <div class="mcq-opts">
    <div class="mcq-opt" onclick="answer(this,'q15',false)"><span class="letter">A</span> CN III palsy; parasympathetic disruption</div>
    <div class="mcq-opt" onclick="answer(this,'q15',true)"><span class="letter">B</span> Horner's syndrome; sympathetic disruption</div>
    <div class="mcq-opt" onclick="answer(this,'q15',false)"><span class="letter">C</span> CN VII palsy; motor disruption</div>
    <div class="mcq-opt" onclick="answer(this,'q15',false)"><span class="letter">D</span> Argyll Robertson pupil; syphilitic infection</div>
  </div>
  <div class="mcq-explain" id="q15-exp">Horner's syndrome = Miosis + Ptosis + Anhidrosis = sympathetic chain disruption. Miosis = unopposed parasympathetic (dilator paralyzed). Ptosis = loss of Müller's muscle innervation (not levator, so partial ptosis). Anhidrosis = no sympathetic supply to sweat glands. CN III palsy = mydriasis (dilated pupil), not miosis.</div>
</div>

