    <div class="mcq-opt" onclick="answer(this,'q16',false)"><span class="letter">C</span> Grade 4</div>
    <div class="mcq-opt" onclick="answer(this,'q16',false)"><span class="letter">D</span> Grade 1</div>
  </div>
  <div class="mcq-explain" id="q16-exp">MRC Grade 3 = Full range of motion AGAINST GRAVITY, but no resistance can be applied. Grade 4 = full range + some resistance. Grade 2 = only moves when gravity eliminated. Grade 1 = flicker only.</div>
</div>

<!-- Q17 -->
<div class="mcq" id="q17">
  <div class="mcq-num">Question 17</div>
  <div class="mcq-q">A patient with a right parietal lobe lesion is asked to draw a clock. They draw all numbers only on the right side of the clock, omitting the left. What phenomenon is this?</div>
  <div class="mcq-opts">
    <div class="mcq-opt" onclick="answer(this,'q17',false)"><span class="letter">A</span> Anosognosia</div>
    <div class="mcq-opt" onclick="answer(this,'q17',false)"><span class="letter">B</span> Constructional apraxia</div>
    <div class="mcq-opt" onclick="answer(this,'q17',true)"><span class="letter">C</span> Left hemispatial inattention/neglect</div>
    <div class="mcq-opt" onclick="answer(this,'q17',false)"><span class="letter">D</span> Astereognosia</div>
  </div>
  <div class="mcq-explain" id="q17-exp">Left hemispatial inattention/neglect: Right parietal lobe lesions cause patients to fail to attend to the LEFT half of space. They will draw the right half of figures accurately but make errors on the left. Classic test = clock drawing (crowded numbers on right side).</div>
</div>

<!-- Q18 -->
<div class="mcq" id="q18">
  <div class="mcq-num">Question 18</div>
  <div class="mcq-q">Cheyne-Stokes respiration (crescendo-decrescendo breathing alternating with apnea) in a comatose patient localizes the lesion to:</div>
  <div class="mcq-opts">
    <div class="mcq-opt" onclick="answer(this,'q18',false)"><span class="letter">A</span> Upper diencephalon</div>
    <div class="mcq-opt" onclick="answer(this,'q18',true)"><span class="letter">B</span> Lower diencephalon / forebrain</div>
    <div class="mcq-opt" onclick="answer(this,'q18',false)"><span class="letter">C</span> Midbrain</div>
    <div class="mcq-opt" onclick="answer(this,'q18',false)"><span class="letter">D</span> Rostral pons</div>
  </div>
  <div class="mcq-explain" id="q18-exp">Cheyne-Stokes = LOWER diencephalon (forebrain) lesion. Also seen in metabolic encephalopathy and bilateral cortical dysfunction. Midbrain = central neurogenic hyperventilation. Rostral pons = apneustic breathing. Lower pons = ataxic breathing. Upper medulla = respiratory arrest.</div>
</div>

<!-- Q19 -->
<div class="mcq" id="q19">
  <div class="mcq-num">Question 19</div>
  <div class="mcq-q">The PPRF (Parapontine Reticular Formation) receives input from the contralateral FEF and sends signals to the IPSILATERAL CN VI nucleus. If there is a DESTRUCTIVE lesion of the LEFT PPRF, where will the patient's eyes be deviated?</div>
  <div class="mcq-opts">
    <div class="mcq-opt" onclick="answer(this,'q19',false)"><span class="letter">A</span> Toward the left (ipsilateral to lesion)</div>
    <div class="mcq-opt" onclick="answer(this,'q19',true)"><span class="letter">B</span> Toward the right (away from the lesion)</div>
    <div class="mcq-opt" onclick="answer(this,'q19',false)"><span class="letter">C</span> Downward bilaterally</div>
    <div class="mcq-opt" onclick="answer(this,'q19',false)"><span class="letter">D</span> No change in gaze</div>
  </div>
  <div class="mcq-explain" id="q19-exp">Destructive PPRF lesion → eyes deviate AWAY from the lesion (ipsilateral gaze palsy). The LEFT PPRF normally drives LEFT gaze; destroy it and the patient cannot look LEFT → eyes deviate to the RIGHT. Compare with FEF: destructive FEF lesion → eyes look TOWARD the lesion (FEF normally drives contralateral gaze).</div>
</div>

